  2. Google Fonts fetch implementation — does it exist?

  No. Zero code anywhere. No fetch/download/HTTP, no .ttf cache logic, no CTFontManagerRegisterFontsForURL. The only google
  hit was a false positive (gcconfig.h). The current font system is the opposite model — a local /System/Library/Fonts
  directory scan. So the Google Fonts fetch/cache and the one-call CTFontManagerRegisterFontsForURL Apple seam are 100%
  greenfield.

  3. Config / API-key file location

  No existing config-file convention in the repo. The established outside-repo support location is ~/data/support/ — it
  already holds Include/groups.ext, Frame, Maps, symlinked into the tree. That's the natural, git-safe home for a secret
  Google Fonts API key (never enters the repo). In-repo gitignored alternatives exist (XML-Incant/, BeforeRefactor/, …) but a
  secret belongs outside git. Recommendation: ~/data/support/ (e.g. a fontsAPI.key or small config file there). Greenfield
  decision.

  4. Form font-attribute conformance

  The 11 converted forms contain only font references — font=normal|title|header and barewords
  titleFont/headerFont/normalFont/copperFont. These name a style; they carry no inline family/size/bold/italic, so nothing in
  the forms violates the agreed format — they're references, not definitions.

  The format problem lives in the definitions, and there are four divergent variants in the tree, none matching the agreed
  one:

  ┌────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │           Source           │                                  Form                                  │
  ├────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Controls/attributes.xml:82 │ <courierFont font='bold 24px "Courier New"'/> (CSS string)             │
  ├────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ htmlTraits.xml:118         │ <courierFont font="Courier New" fontSize=24 bold/> (font= + fontSize=) │
  ├────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ WorkingOn/drawing:158      │ courierFont="Courier New" size=24.0 bold (value=family, size=)         │
  ├────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Agreed                     │ <courierFont family="Courier New" size=24 bold/> (family= + size=)     │
  └────────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  And the code (setFont) reads name (field text) + size/bold/italic — matching none exactly (closest to WorkingOn/drawing,
  but wants size not fontSize, and the family as the field value, not a family= attribute). Adopting the agreed family=
  format requires updating setFont to read family and consolidating all definition files onto one format.

  5. ParseXML color grammar vs cOLOr hex — convergence

  - ParseXML lives in Aside/ (gitignored backup): Aside/BeforeSimple/ParseXML.{g,act,rtn,twk,mm,h},
  Aside/WithJIT/ParseXML.{g,act,rtn}. Your updated color grammar is offline work — not in the active tree, so I can't diff it
  directly.
  - cOLOr registry hex format is consistent: <name=#rrggbb/> — 6 hex digits, # prefix (some carry extra gradient=/angle=,
  e.g. radialGreen).
  - One divergence to flag: setColor (Stylish.twk:63) validates strlen == 6 and sscanf %x — it expects 6 chars without #, but
  the registry stores #ef2b2d (7 chars). So there's a #-stripping assumption between the registry value and setColor —
  either the parser strips # upstream or it's a latent mismatch. When your updated ParseXML lands, confirm it emits a 6-char
  hex (or that # is stripped before setColor).

  Assessment — greenfield vs partially built

  Roughly two-thirds greenfield, one-third partially-built-but-fragmented. Everything on the Google Fonts axis is greenfield:
  there is no fetch, no .ttf cache, and no CTFontManagerRegisterFontsForURL registration seam — and the existing font
  machinery is the local-directory-scanner model you're explicitly replacing, so it's discard-not-extend. Above that seam,
  though, the style-application layer is genuinely partially built: Stylish.twk already turns hex into a Color and
  name/size/bold/italic into an NSFont, the cOLOr hex registry is established and consumed, and decomposed font attributes
  are already partially understood by setFont. The real non-greenfield work isn't writing that layer from scratch — it's
  consolidation: four competing font-definition formats need to collapse onto the agreed family/size/bold/italic
  decomposition, setFont needs to read family, and the color path needs the #-handling confirmed against your updated
  ParseXML grammar. Net: build the fetch+registration plumbing fresh; refactor (don't rebuild) the style/registry layer onto
  the agreed format.
